To set the cart ready position, use the CART UP/DOWN switch to move the cart to the desired ready height. Then, select "Set Ready Position" on this screen. The "deadband" setting on this screen adjusts the range of the sensor that is considered to be at ready height.

The distance calibration can be set using a guided procedure, or the calibration number can be manually edited.
To calibrate distances, you must drive a pre-measured calibration course of preferably 300 feet or greater.\nAfter driving the course, you will be prompted to enter the distance of the course.

Now, drive the truck a known distance.  The distance you have traveled, according to the current calibration, is displayed below.\n\nAfter you have driven the known distance, press "Finished driving" to correct the distance.

How far did you actually drive the truck?
Correct the distance shown below to match the course length.


Once you have entered the exact distance you traveled, press "Continue" to complete the calibration process.
To accept the new calibration numbers, press "Save."  To keep the old calibration, press "Abort."
The GPS DR (dead reckoning) feature is calibrated automatically or using a guided procedure.  Gyro alignment parameters may need to be entered manually.
The X axis is in the direction of forward movement.\nThe Y axis is positive to the right.  The Z axis is positive down.\nPositive rotation around an axis uses the right-hand rule.

Changing the gyro orientation will reset the current calibration information.  If you don't want to redo the dead reckoning calibration, you should select "Cancel" then "Abort."\nOtherwise, select "Finish."
A solid GPS fix must be obtained to begin.\nPlease start in open sky with minimal chance of nearby electromagnetic reflections and press "Begin Calibrating" when a fix has been obtained.

Dead reckoning calibration requires travel faster than 12.5 mph (20 km/h) for several minutes.  Approximately 8 to 12 turns in each direction (left/right) should be performed.  The calibration status is monitored and this procedure will continue automatically when calibration is complete.
Calibration of the dead reckoning system has been completed.  Press "Save Calibration" to store this calibration.  GPS processing will be interrupted briefly while the save takes place.

Given the current calibration number, the calibration quantity seems to be too low.  If the calibration is at fault, it may need to be adjusted manually before running this calibration procedure.\n\nPress "Exit."

To calibrate the selected laser sensor, mount the laser sensor level with the uncut road, at least 31 inches above the surface. Press "Set Calibration" to treat this position as 0, or "Cancel" to exit.
Clearing a laser sensor's calibration will allow it to read true distance values with no correction. Press "Clear Calibration" to clear the selected laser sensor's calibration, or "Cancel" to exit.
A laser sensor can be calibrated,\nor reset to default settings.
Resetting a laser will clear the settings back to the default values necessary for use with your GC-12 grinder. Press "Reset Laser Settings" to reset the selected laser sensor, or "Cancel" to exit.

Calibrations Setup
A pump calibration can be set using a guided procedure, or the calibration number can be manually edited.
Pump calibration requires at least 5 pump strokes to be counted.  Ensure you are using enough paint for the calibration process.
To calibrate a pump, you must fill a pre-measured container that is preferably at least 5 gallons.  After filling the container, you will be prompted to enter its volume.

Fill the paint container with the known volume of paint. The amount of paint that has been pumped, according to the current calibration, is displayed below. The true paint volume will be corrected in the final step.
Enter the actual volume of your pre-measured container.
Move the saw to the touch position visually, then press the "Set Touch" button.  Press "Abort" to stop the calibration.

The calibration values entered require saw adjustments that exceed the minimum or maximum actuator targets.  The calibration is discarded.  If there was an error entering the plunge depth values, you can re-enter them.  Otherwise, you can exit the calibration by pressing the "Exit" button.

To calibrate the plunge depth, you need to do a test plunge.  Make sure the plunge depth shown below is correct.  Move the cart to the ready position, turn the saw on, and press and hold the "plunge cut" switch to do the test plunge.  This screen will update when the plunge is complete, or you can select "Abort" to cancel.
Now, physically measure the depth of each side of the completed test plunge and enter it below. When you're finished, select "Done."
